The paper deals with the problem of causal discovery from empirical data, which is a fundamental problem in many scientific domains. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) sub-category. The paper proposes a polynomial time algorithm for learning the exact correctly-oriented structure of the transitive reduction of any causal Bayesian network with high probability, which involves statistical learning. This suggests that the paper is also likely to belong to the Machine Learning (cs.LG) sub-category. The paper also involves theoretical analysis of sample complexity, which suggests that it could belong to the Discrete Mathematics (cs.DM) sub-category. The paper also involves information theory, as it discusses the number of interventional path queries required for learning the network, which suggests that it could belong to the Information Theory (cs.IT) sub-category. Finally, the paper involves statistical inference and causal modeling, which suggests that it could belong to the Social and Information Networks (cs.SI) sub-category.
